<Layout title="Betong Magazine — Pablo Anttila">
  <main>
    <nav aria-label="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/work">← All work</a>
    </nav>

    <header>
      <small>2009–2014</small>
      <h1>Betong Magazine</h1>
      <p>Editorial Platform</p>
    </header>

    <figure>
      <p>[Project screenshot]</p>
    </figure>

    <article>
      <h2>What</h2>
      <p>Betong.se — the largest Swedish online publication for concrete industry news. Daily coverage of architecture, design, research, and construction. A niche audience, but deeply engaged.</p>

      <h2>My role</h2>
      <p>Freelance Web Designer and Developer. Designed, developed, and maintained the platform over five years while building reader community features.</p>

      <h2>What I built</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Weekly polls</strong> — Community engagement features</li>
        <li><strong>Newsletter system</strong> — Content-driven email campaigns</li>
        <li><strong>Annual gala voting</strong> — Interactive voting system for industry awards</li>
        <li><strong>Q&A interface</strong> — Community-driven question and answer platform</li>
        <li><strong>Platform maintenance</strong> — Hosting, plugins, and ongoing development</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Stack</h2>
      <p>
        {['WordPress', 'PHP', 'MySQL', 'HTML', 'CSS', 'JavaScript'].map(tech => (
          <code>{tech}</code>
        ))}
      </p>

      <h2>Impact</h2>
      <p><strong>Over 1 million unique pageviews</strong> during my time as developer. For a niche B2B publication, that's significant reach.</p>

      <h2>Why it matters</h2>
      <p>This freelance work became the backbone of my early career. Long-term client relationship, real editorial constraints, and direct feedback loop with readers. It taught me that good work comes from understanding your audience deeply.</p>
    </article>

    <nav>
      <a href="/work/design-mobile">← Design Mobile</a>
      <a href="/work">All projects →</a>
    </nav>
  </main>
</Layout>
